From bd18a8bd71753b8321e513fe19cb724345f6b873 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Sun, 28 Jun 2026 01:17:33 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] darlingserver: progress + timing metrics over an abstract
 UNIX socket

perf #0 (dar-dar6x4-perf-5dq.6): add an in-server observability channel so tooling
can reliably tell "slow but progressing" from "genuinely wedged", and measure the
per-RPC latency the perf epic must drive down. Without this, external proxies
(log-file size, CPU%, /proc snapshots) conflate slow with hung -- that misdiagnosed
dar-l3a (a slow gettext build) as a stall.

Server:
  - Metrics singleton (metrics.{hpp,cpp}): lock-free atomic counters
    (rpcs_serviced, replies_sent, messages_received, checkins, forks) and log2-bucketed
    latency histograms (rpc/checkin/fork) exposing p50/p95/p99/max. Hot-path increments
    use relaxed atomics; quantiles are computed from buckets at snapshot time (no
    per-sample storage/allocation).
  - Stat socket: a SOCK_STREAM listener in the ABSTRACT namespace. The server runs in a
    private mount namespace (launcher joins darling-init's mnt ns) so a pathname socket
    is unreachable from the host; the network namespace IS shared, so an abstract name
    (keyed off the prefix) works for host-side tooling. On connect the main event loop
    writes a one-shot JSON snapshot and closes -- single-threaded, so the atomic reads
    are consistent. Best-effort: any setup failure leaves it disabled and the server
    runs normally.
  - Instrumentation points: messages_received in the inbox pop loop; replies_sent +
    last_reply time in MessageQueue::sendMany; rpcs_serviced + rpc/checkin latency around
    processCall() in microthreadWorker; checkins/forks + fork latency in Checkin.
  - WorkQueue::stats() exposes depth / workers busy/total for the snapshot gauges.

Tooling:
  - darling-stat: connect + print one JSON snapshot.
  - darling-progress-watch: sample every N s and classify PROGRESSING / SLOW (rpcs up but
    checkin/fork pXX above threshold == the dar-l3a state) / WEDGED (flat AND
    clients_blocked>0 AND last_reply_age large) / IDLE (flat, nobody blocked). Replaces
    the unreliable "log frozen" heuristic.

Tests (RED->GREEN, committed with the fix per the standing TDD rule):
  - tests/metrics_histogram_test.cpp: hermetic unit test of histogram bucketing/quantiles
    (fast workload -> low pXX, 480ms workload -> high pXX, mixed -> tail visible) and the
    JSON snapshot fields. Links only metrics.cpp; no server boot.
  - tests/progress_classifier_test.py: runs the real classify() over 6 cases; pins the
    SLOW-vs-WEDGED distinction the old log-frozen heuristic got wrong (proven RED when
    reverted to "flat == wedged").

Live-validated: abstract socket reachable from the host across the mount namespace;
darling-stat returns a full snapshot; darling-progress-watch reports PROGRESSING
throughout a fork-heavy guest workload (+~4000 rpc/iv, fork p50 16us).

Bead: dar-dar6x4-perf-5dq.6

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
